{"id":"east-tennessee-crossing","generatedAt":"2026-07-10T18:38:22.736Z","designation":"National Scenic Byway","parkCode":null,"source":{"roadArticle":"East Tennessee Crossing Byway","revisionId":1302554318,"url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/East_Tennessee_Crossing_Byway"},"attribution":{"license":"CC BY-SA 4.0","licenseUrl":"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/","articleUrl":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/East_Tennessee_Crossing_Byway","text":"Route, junction, and history details adapted from the Wikipedia article \"East Tennessee Crossing Byway\", by Wikipedia contributors, licensed under CC BY-SA 4.0."},"sources":[{"name":"Wikipedia","src":"wikipedia","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/East_Tennessee_Crossing_Byway","revisionId":1302554318,"retrievedAt":"2026-07-10T18:38:22.736Z"},{"name":"Federal Highway Administration — National Scenic Byways","src":"fhwa","url":"https://www.fhwa.dot.gov/byways","retrievedAt":"2026-07-10T18:38:22.736Z"},{"name":"OpenStreetMap contributors (ODbL)","src":"osm","url":"https://www.openstreetmap.org/copyright","retrievedAt":"2026-07-10T18:38:22.736Z"}],"endpoints":{"from":"Cherokee National Forest, TN","to":"Cumberland Gap National Historical Park, TN","via":["Leadvale, TN","Thorn Hill, TN","Cumberland Gap, TN"]},"itinerary":[{"seq":1,"place":"Cherokee National Forest","state":"TN","kind":"terminus","mileFromStart":0,"toNextMi":null,"note":"The drive begins here","control":["Hot Springs","Wolf Creek Bridge over the French Broad River"],"lat":35.91788,"lng":-82.9123,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":2,"place":"Del Rio","state":"TN","kind":"town","mileFromStart":null,"toNextMi":null,"note":"Junction toward Greeneville","control":["Greeneville","Parrottsville"],"lat":35.92565,"lng":-83.02748,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":3,"place":"Bridgeport","state":"TN","kind":"crossing","mileFromStart":null,"toNextMi":null,"note":"Crosses Major J.T. Huff Bridge","control":["Major J.T. Huff Bridge over the French Broad River"],"lat":35.95294,"lng":-83.11706,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":4,"place":"Newport","state":"TN","kind":"town","mileFromStart":null,"toNextMi":null,"note":"Junction toward Cosby","control":["Cosby","John W. Fisher Bridge over the Pigeon River","Greeneville","Gatlinburg","White Pine","Morristown","Dandridge"],"lat":35.96731,"lng":-83.19682,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":5,"place":"Douglas Lake/French Broad River","state":"TN","kind":"crossing","mileFromStart":null,"toNextMi":null,"note":"Crosses J. W. Walters Bridge","control":["J. W. Walters Bridge"],"lat":null,"lng":null,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":6,"place":"Leadvale","state":"TN","kind":"town","mileFromStart":null,"toNextMi":null,"note":"Junction toward Baneberry","control":["Baneberry"],"lat":null,"lng":null,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":7,"place":"White Pine","state":"TN","kind":"town","mileFromStart":null,"toNextMi":null,"note":"Junction toward Talbott","control":["Talbott","Dandridge"],"lat":36.1116,"lng":-83.28497,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":8,"place":"Morristown","state":"TN","kind":"town","mileFromStart":null,"toNextMi":null,"note":"Junction toward Knoxville & Bristol","control":["Knoxville","Bristol","Downtown","Whitesburg","College Square Drive","College Park Drive","Morristown","Jefferson City","Greeneville","Morristown Central Business District"],"lat":36.2047,"lng":-83.26665,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":9,"place":"Cherokee Lake/Holston River","state":"TN","kind":"crossing","mileFromStart":null,"toNextMi":null,"note":"Crosses Olen R. Marshall Memorial Bridge","control":["Olen R. Marshall Memorial Bridge"],"lat":null,"lng":null,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":10,"place":"Bean Station","state":"TN","kind":"town","mileFromStart":null,"toNextMi":null,"note":"Junction toward German Creek & Cherokee","control":["German Creek","Cherokee","Rogersville","Kingsport","Rutledge","Knoxville"],"lat":36.33887,"lng":-83.29045,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":11,"place":"Thorn Hill","state":"TN","kind":"town","mileFromStart":null,"toNextMi":null,"note":"Junction toward Washburn & Treadway","control":["Washburn","Treadway"],"lat":36.35081,"lng":-83.41205,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":12,"place":"Springdale","state":"TN","kind":"town","mileFromStart":null,"toNextMi":null,"note":"Junction toward Sneedville","control":["Sneedville"],"lat":null,"lng":null,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":13,"place":"Tazewell","state":"TN","kind":"town","mileFromStart":null,"toNextMi":null,"note":"Junction toward New Tazewell & Maynardville","control":["New Tazewell","Maynardville"],"lat":36.38267,"lng":-83.44723,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":14,"place":"Powell River","state":"TN","kind":"crossing","mileFromStart":null,"toNextMi":null,"note":"Crosses Powell River","control":["Powell River Bridge"],"lat":null,"lng":null,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":15,"place":"Harrogate","state":"TN","kind":"town","mileFromStart":null,"toNextMi":null,"note":"Junction toward Hopewell & Sneedville","control":["Hopewell","Sneedville","Arthur","Speedwell","Fincastle","LaFollette"],"lat":36.38267,"lng":-83.44723,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":16,"place":"Cumberland Gap","state":"TN","kind":"crossing","mileFromStart":null,"toNextMi":null,"note":"Junction toward Cumberland Gap & TN","control":["Cumberland Gap","TN","Jonesville","VA"],"lat":36.38267,"lng":-83.44723,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":17,"place":"Cumberland Gap National Historical Park","state":"TN","kind":"terminus","mileFromStart":null,"toNextMi":null,"note":"The drive ends here","control":["Cumberland Gap Tunnel"],"lat":36.38267,"lng":-83.44723,"src":"wikipedia"}],"history":{"paragraphs":["What is now the East Tennessee Crossing Byway was supposedly first traversed by Native Americans, long before the area was settled by European pioneers. During this period, the route was considered a part of the Cherokee Warriors' Path. Most notably, the Cumberland Gap to Bean Station section of the route was used as a pathway to Kentucky on famous pioneer and settler, Daniel Boone's Wilderness Road.","In 1915, the Cumberland Gap to Morristown section was designated a part of the Dixie Highway, one of the routes in the National Auto Trail system, which was one of the earliest highway systems developed in the United States.","Throughout the early to mid-20th century, the route from the Cumberland Gap to Tazewell, along with SR 33 from Tazewell to Knoxville, was part of the infamous Thunder Road, which was used by bootleggers to illegally transport and trade moonshine. The story was later fictionally adapted into a 1958 crime-drama film and song of the same name.","Based on the overall historical significance and proximity to historic sites such as the tavern once lived in by Davy Crockett in Morristown, the Battle of Bean's Station site in Grainger County, and the Appalachian Trail in the Cherokee National Forest, many local historians called for US 25E and US 25 to the North Carolina state line to become a scenic byway. After a lengthy nomination and funding process, the efforts proved successful, as the East Tennessee Crossing National Scenic Byway was officially established in late 2009."],"sourceSection":"History","src":"wikipedia"},"highlights":[{"n":"Cherokee National Forest","d":"The drive begins here","q":"Cherokee National Forest","lat":36.48333333,"lng":-82.08333333,"src":"wikipedia"},{"n":"Bridgeport","d":"Crosses Major J.T. Huff Bridge","q":"Bridgeport","lat":35.95305556,"lng":-83.11722222,"src":"wikipedia"},{"n":"Cumberland Gap","d":"Junction toward Cumberland Gap & TN","q":"Cumberland Gap","lat":36.59888889,"lng":-83.66722222,"src":"wikipedia"}],"references":[{"n":1,"text":"\"East Tennessee Crossing\". Federal Highway Administration. Archived from the original on October 5, 2013. Retrieved July 15, 2020.","url":"https://web.archive.org/web/20131005085609/http://www.fhwa.dot.gov/byways/byways/76017"},{"n":2,"text":"Shearer, John (November 7, 2009). \"Highway 25E earns byway designation\". The Knoxville News Sentinel. Retrieved July 15, 2020.","url":"http://archive.knoxnews.com/news/local/highway-25e-earns-byway-designation-ep-409378626-359109521.html"},{"n":3,"text":"O'Neil, Duay (October 20, 2009). \"Hwy 25 East is Now a National Scenic Byway\". The Newport Plain Talk. Archived from the original on July 14, 2011. Retrieved October 23, 2009.","url":"https://web.archive.org/web/20110714173015/http://www.newportplaintalk.com/story/30367"},{"n":4,"text":"\"East Tennessee Crossing Byway\". Tennessee Vacation. Retrieved July 16, 2020.","url":"https://www.tnvacation.com/byways/east-tennessee/east-tennessee-crossing-byway"},{"n":5,"text":"\"East Tennessee Crossing Byway\" (Map). Google Maps. Retrieved July 15, 2020.","url":"https://www.google.com/maps/dir/36.597872,+-83.676059/35.9178554,-82.9123667/@36.2558846,-83.5741994,10z/data=!3m1!4b1!4m6!4m5!1m3!2m2!1d-83.676059!2d36.597872!1m0"},{"n":6,"text":"Bowers, Larry (January 3, 2016). \"Deciphering fact from fiction of 'Thunder Road'\". Cleveland Daily Banner. Archived from the original on March 3, 2019. Retrieved July 20, 2020.","url":"https://web.archive.org/web/20190303155307/http://clevelandbanner.com/stories/deciphering-fact-from-fiction-of-thunder-road,25146"},{"n":7,"text":"Thunder Road (1958) at IMDb","url":"https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0052293/"},{"n":8,"text":"\"Tenn. Earns Two National Scenic Byways\". Road & Bridges. October 19, 2009. Retrieved July 20, 2020.","url":"https://www.roadsbridges.com/tenn-earns-two-national-scenic-byways"}],"routeLine":[[35.91788,-82.9123],[35.91821,-82.91406],[35.91835,-82.91488],[35.91829,-82.9157],[35.91811,-82.91665],[35.91768,-82.91747],[35.91717,-82.91828],[35.91695,-82.91896],[35.91603,-82.91988],[35.91557,-82.92061],[35.91535,-82.92148],[35.91532,-82.92237],[35.91558,-82.92305],[35.91631,-82.92399],[35.91681,-82.92457],[35.91694,-82.92547],[35.91687,-82.92638],[35.91654,-82.92711],[35.91598,-82.92786],[35.91585,-82.92865],[35.91519,-82.92944],[35.91474,-82.93009],[35.91458,-82.93092],[35.91484,-82.93161],[35.91506,-82.93241],[35.9152,-82.93355],[35.91535,-82.93493],[35.91556,-82.